                    <item>
              <title>Online teamworking to develop a business case</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/294</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/294</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[As an alternative to a three-day residential school, this course offers an online equivalent in which students not only work on the same group task – developing a business case – but run through a sequence of activities to establish their ability to work as a team in the online environment.

Across an 18 day period, the students first learn to make their thinking explicit through activities such as deciding as a group whether each of a set of statements is true or false. Next they discuss and propose solutions to work-based problems. Only after that do they start work on the business case for an imaginary company – the scenario being designed to be too big for any student to complete on their own, requiring them to divide up the tasks.
 
As a final stage, the students review the business case they have produced, their team processes, and the exercise as a whole.

[Sheila Tyler]
]]></description>
          <pubDate>Tue, 29 Jul 2008 07:06:30 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Computer-marked assessment (law)</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/275</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/275</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>This law course had a problem with poor student performance in a compulsory introductory module which was supposed to establish basic factual knowledge and reasoning skill. Student feedback showed that they often did not understand what was expected of them until their assessment.
<p>
So the lecturer created a series of online quizzes to provide formative assessment throughout the module. The immediacy of the feedback compensated for its necessary brevity and generic nature, and a study found that those students who took the quizzes did better in all aspects of the final examination, including higher order cognitive skills such as synthesis and evaluation.

[Paul Catley]
]]></description>
          <pubDate>Tue, 29 Jul 2008 06:35:37 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
